        Bypass brewing only works when the concentrated brew still tastes good after dilution. That sounds obvious, but plenty of
        recipes fall apart the second you top them up. We cared most about repeatability, taste balance after adding water,
        workflow friction, and how much each recipe depends on extra gear. If the recipe is fussy enough that you will stop using it
        by Wednesday, it is not a great recipe.
      </p>
      <p>
        We also paid attention to what the reader actually experiences in the cup. Does the coffee stay sweet after dilution, or
        does it go flat like watered-down diner coffee? Does the press feel smooth, or like you are trying to crush a brick? The
        best AeroPress bypass methods keep the clarity people love about AeroPress while stretching the cup size without wrecking it.
      </p>
    </section>
